@ICPC To help get problems submitted, you can follow the below steps to create a pull request with your problem solutions. Let me know if you run into any issues and I can help debug. As a backup you can always email me a zip of your code and I can push for you :)

1. Go to **https://github.com/markfloryan/uvaicpc**
2. For the repo by clicking the `Fork` button in the top right and select your username (this should take you to https://github.com/<username>/uvaicpc)
3. Get the forked repo url by clicking the green code button and clicking the copy button next to the HTTPS url
4. Go to your comandline and pull your forked repo by typing `git clone https://github.com/<username>/uvaicpc.git` (where the URL is the one you copied).
5. Move your files into the newly created `uvaicpc` folder under the correct problem
6. While in the root directory of the project (inside /uvaicpc so that if you type ls you can see the various project set folders) commit your files by doing the following:
    6.1. `git add .`
    6.2. `git commit -am "Daniel - problems 1,2"` (this comment is just an example and you should include your own name and the problems you are submitting)
    6.3. `git push`
7. Head on over to https://github.com/markfloryan/uvaicpc/compare to begin opening a pull request
8. Under the header **Compare Changes** click **compare across forks**
9. Change the **head repository** field and to your forked repo (<username>/uvaicpc)
10. Create the pull request
11. Profit because Professors Floryan and Brunelle will know you did a good job!

If you don't have a terminal that has git installed, I am a windows user and a big fan of **gitbash** (https://gitforwindows.org/). You can also use a gui based system like **githubdesktop** that is more visually appealing that a terminal window.

Hi everyone - After last meeting on Wednesday, I was curious about the 'shuffles' problem (https://open.kattis.com/problems/shuffles). This problem kind of stumped us a bit (though I see now that one team had a solution and I suppose wasn't present on Wednesday).

If you're curious, I added my solution to the repo (I became uncharacteristically motivated). The short version is you go through once and count how many unique 'runs' of numbers are already in relative correct order. For example, 2 1 4 3 6 5 8 7 has 5 unique runs. 1, 2 3, 4 5, 6 7, and 8 are all in relative correct order. If you count the number of these "runs", the solution is ceiling(log_2(num_runs)).

If you curious about the intuition, it is because on each unshuffle (if we are working backwards) we can take two of these runs and put one in one half of the split and one run in the other, putting the two runs completely in correct relative order. We can do this for each adjacent pair of runs, which approximately halving the number of runs each time. We don't need to simulate this, it will always just happen...so the number of times is always ceiling(log_2(num_runs)). Hope this helps.

I looked up the solution. First, everything is coordinate compressed. Then, they maintain an array of stacks that contain raindrops at a given x with the stack sorted in order of the y values (top of stack has lowest y value). In addition, they use a segment tree that will find the min y raindrop over a range of x. Then they process the sensors in order of highest y to lowest. Each time they just query the ST for which raindrop will hit it (the min y value in the range of the sensor) and then the update the ST by popping off the raindrop from the stack and propagating the change through the ST.

First, consider the question if only '(' and ')' were the characters. It would be possible to iterate over all possible strings since string length was at most 20. Given a bracket sequence of '(' and ')' (assume it's a valid one), it would be easy to see which open and closed parentheses are paired with each other. If two paired parentheses were '?' in the original string, then there would be 4 possible choices for that pairing. Otherwise, there would be only one way to choose that pairing. So the answer for that ordering of '(' and ')' is just 4^k where k is the number of '?'s that get paired. Iterating over all 2^20 possible orderings of '(' and ')' and summing the answers (after checking that the current ordering is valid given the original string) will give you the answer.
Yep, that was my thought on that one as well. You can do exponential since the length is 20, you just need to count all four possible bracket options at once instead of trying them individually.
